==Spanish==

===Etymology===
From {{L.|es}} ''[[sto#Latin|stō]]'', “[[stand]]”

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/estˈaɾ/}}

===Verb===
'''estar'''

# To have a (transient) location in space. Cf. ''[[ser]]'', ''[[quedar]]''.
#:''¿Dónde '''estás'''?''—“Where are you?”
#:'''''Estoy''' en casa.''—“I am at home.”
# Denotes a copula, in a transient fashion. Cf. ''[[ser]]''.
#:''El tiempo '''estaba''' frío.''—“The weather was cold [back then].”
#:''¿'''Estás''' loco?''—“Are you crazy [right now]?”
# Auxiliary verb for the progressive tense; precedes verb in gerund.
#:''Ella '''está''' cantando.''—“She is singing.”

====Conjugation====

{{Template:es:-ar(estar)}}

====Usage notes====
Portuguese and Spanish have two different verbs that are usually translated to English as “to be”: '''''ser''''' relates to '''[[essence]]''', contrasting with ''[[estar]]'', which relates to '''[[state]]'''.  Contrast the following:
* ''El hombre '''está''' felíz.''—“The man is [currently] happy.”
* ''El hombre '''es''' felíz.''—“The man is [always] happy.”
* ''¿'''Estás''' loco?''—“Are you crazy [currently out of your mind]?”
* ''¿'''Eres''' loco?''—“Are you crazy [permanently insane]?”

====Derived terms====
*'''''estar''' [[por]]'' + infinitive: “to [[be]] to be done”, “to be (still) undone”:
*:''[[esto#Finnish|Esto]] todavía '''está''' por [[hacer]].''—“This is still to be done.”

